            <h6>Values</h6>
            <p>I believe that people should only work towards goals which align with their values, and that the only reason to collaborate
            is to work towards common goals. Therefore, shared values are the foundation of any working relationship. It is a flaw of our
            tech-era collaborative tools (and indeed capitalist collaboration in general) that everybody shares what they can do, but not why 
            they want to do those things. I will address this problem here.
            <br/>
            I care about conserving the natural beauty of our world, which I believe to be an elementary piece of human health and joy.
            I believe that intellectual curiousity is the noblest human craving, and a natural consequence of the decision to appreciate life.
            Extending this, I think that education is the single most important social system.
            I think that healthy relationships with other people are the single most important ingredient of a full life, although I admit that I often
            fall short in supporting these.
            Ultimately, I would argue that while solipsism is logically inevitable, it is more fruitful to pursue an
            intangible sense of universal harmony based on well thought-out moral assumptions (like the protection and continuation of the human historical narrative)
            than it is to pursue a strictly-defined materialist goal based on similar assumptions (like the most happiness for the most people). The former 
            example is what I would say supports my sense of purpose in life, if I were asked to define it.
            </p> 
            
            <br/>
            
            <h6>Vision</h6>
            <p>I believe that we exist during a pivotal moment in the history of life, and I envision a future in which our species thinks and acts with
            unity, purpose, and conscience. I consider it our duty as individuals to strive for this ideal.</p>
